\intbl \ql \b Summary of Evaluator Report\b0 \line The evaluator indicated that Criterion 1 is in need of improvement and that Criterion 3 does not comply with minimum standards. The other criteria are deemed to meet minimum standards. \line \line In terms of Criterion 1\'2C the evaluator indicated that the information regarding programme design and the rationale for the qualification is perhaps a bit too generic and lacks emphasis on the specific qualification.  This is also found to be the case in the rationale for the proposed qualification.  There is no mention of the industry need or need for the specific skills and knowledge in industry that this qualification will equip students with.  The articulation possibilities are mentioned in a broad sense with no specific examples of qualifications to which students can articulate.  \line \line One particular concern raised by the evaluator in terms of Criterion 1 is that the experiential learning \'28Work Integrated Learning - WIL\'29 module is an exit level module at NQF Level 7. It is the evaluator\'27s position that Work Integrated Learning should have an integrated approach where students blend their contextual experience with the conceptual knowledge before completion of the programme and it is therefore not ideal that such a module be a type of capstone module.  Another concern\'2C taking into account the fact that the institution is not accepting responsibility for placement\'2C is that there is no alternative modality for WIL.  If a student fails to find an appropriate placement\'2C the particular student cannot complete the course and obtain the Diploma.  \line \line Another concern is that introductory modules are indicated as being NQF Level 6\'2C e.g. Event Management 1.  One would expect these modules to be at Level 5 considering that they follow from the entry requirement of a NSC or NCV at Level 4 \'28with the required achievement levels in specified learning areas\'29. The credit level for the Integrated Marketing Communications module seems to be very high in relation to the other modules at 30.  The need for the three modules \'28Integrated Marketing Communications 1\'2C 2 \'26 3\'29 is not apparent since this is an aspect that forms part of Marketing Management and there are Marketing Management modules at each level as well.  The details of the separate Integrated Marketing Communications Modules could not be found in the Qualification Structure and Course Curriculum Statement and it seems to be included in Marketing Management. This leads to a concern regarding the calculation of the credits.\line There is a distinct lack of evidence to indicate that the institution has enough adequately qualified lecturing staff with a background in event management or either hospitality or tourism management.  The programme coordinator has no experience or relevant qualifications in the field.\line \line The Directorate cannot support the accreditation of the programme in its current form. \line \line \line \line \cell \pard 

